The '''X2 transceiver''' format is a 10 gigabit per second modular fiber optic interface intended for use in routers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/interfaces-modules/10-gigabit-modules/product_data_sheet0900aecd801f92aa.html|title=Cisco X2 transceivers|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> switches and optical transport platforms. It is an early generation 10 gigabit interface related to the similar [[XENPAK|XENPAK and XPAK]] formats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=x2+transceiver|title=X2 transceiver types|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> X2 may be used with [[10 Gigabit Ethernet|10 gigabit ethernet]] or OC-192/STM-64 speed SDH/[[Synchronous optical networking|SONET]] equipment.
X2 modules are smaller and consume less power than first generation XENPAK modules, but larger and consume more energy than the newer [[XFP transceiver]] standard and [[Small form-factor pluggable transceiver|SFP]]+ standards.
As of 2016 this format is relatively uncommon and has been replaced by 10Gbit/s [[Small form-factor pluggable transceiver|SFP]]+ in most new equipment.
